metadata.name: E s q u a d r o s #36
metadata.description:
Set-square is an instrument in the form of a right triangle, used to draw angles and perpendiculars, in Portuguese we call it Esquadro.

When developing this study, I reflected on the action of order and disorder of alignments, the need I feel when instinctively seeking order and at the same time learning to live with disorder. Programming was like learning to draw all over again, and in Esquadros I try to extrapolate this issue by using simple geometric shapes and slightly playful colors, portraying this phase of starting over.

Esquadros displays some simple variations: density, palettes, a little clutter in some pieces and some inverted colors.

Appreciate the simple shapes and colors that life offers us, even in the midst of a lot of order and disorder. This is my genesis for Fx Hash.

Key controls:

k : save png
l : show pallete label

Artwork by Zizou, @Zizoutez.

Made with p5.js and <3

metadata.name: Vertical World #19
metadata.description:
This artwork is a kind of my inquiry about ambiguous boundaries.
I was a child who liked to draw but always been dissatisfied with my work. Now through coding, I was able to create the "feelings" that I wanted to express. This work is not to imitate a certain landscape or painting style, but simply paint with different brushes, and cooperate with the randomness of the computer.
"I" creates horizontal order, and "computer" creates vertical disorder. My intention is to create
ambiguous visuals in a way that doesn't give specific images, but vague atmosphere.
The meaning is computer-generated and positioned through your eyes.
(It may take more time to render if you using Firefox browser.)

- Press [s] to save png image

Created by haxenfan using p5js.

metadata.name: Crosswalk Monsoon #169
metadata.description:
The story behind this collection is that there isn't really a story behind this collection. It is the result of play, tinkering, and curiosity.

One of the beautiful things about generative art is how we can achieve drastically different results simply by modifying a few parameters or lines of code. As my first release here on fxhash was 'Sabler', it felt fitting that my release for #fxhashturnsone would itself be a modified version of that 'Sabler' algorithm, albeit giving drastically different results.

It is notable for the fact that this is perhaps my most 'chaotic' collection yet, letting go of carefully considered proportions, angles and positioning and here leaving that in the hands of the computer. In a way, this simple act represents several design decisions I never would have imagined myself making a year ago, highlighting my growth as a generative artist over the past year.

It is also a reflection of the inspiration gained from many of the artists and boundary-pushers in the space that each time unlock and encourage creations beyond the immediate comfort zone. For that, this is a 'Thank You' to all of you.

With that, here's to many more years of generative beauty and inspiration on fxhash and beyond.

As with previous collections, I highly recommend viewing the images at full size and savouring the details and the chaos up close. Pressing 'S' will save a 6000 x 6000 px PNG file.

50% of primary sales will be donated to the Processing Foundation.

metadata.name: binary_trees #94
metadata.description:
November, 2022
Little India, Toronto, Canada.


Project Description
---
The word algorithm brings visions of inscrutable equations with latin symbols that can only be understood by people with acronyms after their names. In reality, algorithms can be simple. Very simple in fact.

This project, "binary_trees", uses a simple two step algorithm to search for a secret number. 

For example, to find a secret number between 1 and 100 these are the steps:
Step 1) Pick a number between the lowest number, 1, and the highest number, 100.  
Step 2) If the picked number is higher than the secret number, set the new highest number to be the picked number.  
Or, if the picked number is lower than the secret number, set the new lowest number to be the picked number.  

Repeat Steps 1 and 2 until the secret number is found.

binary_trees repeats hundreds of these searches with each found secret number spawning new searches. Perlin noise, colour selections, arc widths and radii are used to bring a sense of structure to the visual output.

More detail about this project and early development renders can be found in the README.md, README.pdf and test_renders/ folder. 


Five Features 
---
1. Aspect ratios:  
- Landscape
- Portrait
- Square

2. Seven colour palettes   
The colour palettes are adapted from Mark Rothko paintings as interpreted by Merritt Smith, https://github.com/mmerrittsmith/rothko.  

3. Three Organizing Principle Ratios:
- Super Golden Ratio
- PHI
- Golden Angle

4. Number of search trees

5. Maximum Search Space
This feature determines the size of the largest search space to find the secret number. 


Interaction
---
This piece is dimension agnostic and can be exported to PNG format at several different sizes.

The outputs are not scaled but instead re-rendered at each of the dimensions listed below.

Press t: thumbnail @ 200 x 200
Press s: your current screen size
Press p: print size @ 4800 x 4800 which is 16"@300dpi
Press h: HD4K on the vertical @ 2160 x 2160
Press m: Max size @ 10800 x 10800


Acknowledgements and #fxhashTurnsOne
---
binary_trees is a (late) contribution to the first anniversary celebration for fxhash. I am very grateful to the developers/admins/organizers and the community that makes fxhash possible.

A portion of the primary sales are split between the Processing Foundation and Tezos for Iran.

And as always, none of this is possible without my family. Thank you the most to KIRH.

Libraries Used for Development
---
Made with Processing / P5.js
p5.js v1.4.2

metadata.name: Play with lines #zentangle #1
metadata.description:
Once upon a time, there was a sect called the Dotted and the Lined
They considered the point and line sacred!
And they believed that the world started with a point and moved with a line
And the points made the world!


Play with lines
This collection is the result of my playing with the lines I drew with the tablet.
And combining these lines with digital paintings in the background
This set has 7 layers
The first layer contains the background
The second layer of perlin noise lines
The third layer of the lines I have drawn with the tablet is 28 different images in the zentangle style
The fourth layer of lines
The fifth layer of forms on the collection
The sixth and seventh layers include the cover, frame, signature, etc.

metadata.name: Life has no scores #9
metadata.description:
We cannot compose life, at best we hum along to the melodies that life has been played in front of us. Looking back at the scores of our lives, the notations are never neatly noted, but fully felt.  Rewinding the songs of life are our memories, whether sad, happy, angry, or melancholy. It is not clear whether I am dreaming or awake, but our songs all do end. 

In this final drop (for ?), I have reused the first ever class calligraphy(){} I have written from my genesis drop “Nothing comes from nothing”. As time passes, 10 drops later, across almost to the year, I am grateful for the progress I have made, as an artist, and more importantly as a human. After all, what is behind the code of generative art is a human being. 

Scores of music, scrolls of calligraphy, calendar or diary, notating life, time passes, and changes are inevitable. Sometimes we sing louder in laughter and joy, sometimes we scribble in uneasiness, sometimes we just get lost in neon lights. Life goes on. You and me, all the same and yet different.  

There are too many friend artists, friend collectors, fxhash team members, to thank for helping me through this journey. I would like to pay homage to Rudxane in this work, who has taken me under his wings, mentoring and encouraging me in art as well as showing me some degen stuff on the side:-). This homage is not copy-minting, or copying of styles, which I do not have the coding skills to do so even if I wanted to. But it is the influence of taste in many works of Rudxane. In a vague but agreeable taste, I present to you Life has no scores. 

What I was taught was disrupted, and grid studies left unfinished, and oh do we have a BINGO?

Tested on Chrome. Other browsers may render different or not at all (firefox)

Press ‘2’ to save png.
